body:
A couple days ago, it has been reported a [bug in the borrow checker](http://discuss.rust-lang.org/t/borrow-checker-failing-when-providing-trait-object-as-type-parameter). It seems to me that this is more precisely a problem of an incorrect lifetime inferred.

As a memo, this is the reference situation that compiles fine:

``` rust
struct NonGenericStruct;

impl NonGenericStruct {
    fn bar(&self, _: &mut Trait) {}
}   

trait Trait{}

struct FooBar;
impl Trait for FooBar{}

fn main() {
    let mut foobar = FooBar;

    {    // No problem when using non generic struct
        let foo = NonGenericStruct;
        foo.bar(&mut foobar);
        foo.bar(&mut foobar);
    }
}
```

And this is the problematic situation where the lifetime of `GenericStruct` is incorrectly inferred:

``` rust
struct GenericStruct<T>;

impl <T> GenericStruct<T> {
    fn bar(&self, _: T) {}
}

trait Trait{}

struct FooBar;
impl Trait for FooBar{}

fn main() {
    let mut foobar = FooBar;
    {
        let foo = GenericStruct::<&mut Trait>;
        {   
            foo.bar(&mut foobar);   // First borrow passes ...
        }   
        {   
            foo.bar(&mut foobar);   // This fails as "foobar" is already borrowed
        }
    }
}
```

As you can see the only place using the type T is the function, so the lifetime should be bound to the function call and not the object `foo`.
- Is it a limitation of generic in this context ?
- Does that mean that the user has no other option than using a macro here  to emulate the template code generation?
  (That seems a bit odd IMO. It would partially solves the case and make the type `GenericStruct` really hard to use)
